description:
Virtuoso 7.1 has a regression bug for SPARQL VALUES, because doesn't correctly bind more than 1 variable, when more than 1 row of VALUES is given. The following 2 queries work fine:
SELECT ?a
WHERE {
  VALUES ?a {
         "a"
         "b"
  }
}

SELECT ?a ?b
WHERE {
  VALUES (?a ?b) {
         ("a" "ABC")
  }
}

However, when more than 1 variable and more than 1 row is given in the VALUES clause, Virtuoso produces empty bindings for the second (and further) variable(s):
SELECT ?a ?b
WHERE {
  VALUES (?a ?b) {
         ("a" "ABC")
         ("b" "DEF")
  }
}

What's unexpected is that Virtuoso reports the second (and further) variable(s) as bound:
SELECT ?a (BOUND(?b) AS ?bound) # ?bound is projected as true
WHERE {
  VALUES (?a ?b) {
         ("a" "ABC")
         ("b" "DEF")
  }
}

Nevertheless, the query doesn't project the values of the (allegedly) bound variables into the query results.
The previous version of Virtuoso (7.0) didn't have this issue, so I presume this is an regression bug, which could be avoided if test suite like the one for SPARQL 1.1 was employed.
Note: tested with Virtuoso version 07.10.3207 on Linux (x86_64-pc-linux-gnu), Single Server Edition. Virtuoso that runs on DBpedia also suffers from the same regression.
